Upon successful completion of a Ph.D. program, students will be able to:

  • Conduct Original Research: Design, execute, and present original research that contributes new knowledge to the field of study.
  • Master Research Methodology: Apply advanced qualitative, quantitative, and mixed-method research techniques to investigate complex issues.
  • Demonstrate Critical Thinking: Analyze and synthesize academic literature to identify gaps in knowledge and frame new research questions.
  • Advance Scholarly Communication: Produce high-quality academic publications, conference papers, and research presentations.
  • Apply Ethical Research Practices: Uphold ethical standards in research design, data collection, and dissemination of findings.
  • Foster Intellectual Leadership: Lead and contribute to scholarly communities through peer review, collaboration, and academic discourse.
  • Develop Pedagogical Skills: Acquire teaching and mentorship skills to support the next generation of scholars and professionals.
  • Contribute to Theoretical and Practical Knowledge: Bridge theory and practice by developing innovative insights and solutions for real-world challenges.

A PhD in History offers a broad range of career paths in academia, research, public history, government, archives, publishing, and more. Graduates can pursue the following careers:

  1. University Professor or Lecturer: Teach history at the university level, conduct research, and publish scholarly articles and books. History professors often shape academic discourse and mentor the next generation of historians.
  2. Historian or Researcher: Work as a historian for academic institutions, research organizations, museums, or government agencies. Historians conduct original research, analyze primary sources, and contribute to historical scholarship in specific areas or time periods.
  3. Archivist or Curator: Manage historical documents, manuscripts, and artifacts. Archivists work in libraries, museums, and historical sites, preserving and organizing collections for public and scholarly use.
  4. Public Historian: Engage with the public through museums, historical sites, documentaries, and historical consulting. Public historians bring history to life by helping communities understand and appreciate their historical heritage.
  5. Government or Policy Advisor: Use historical research to inform policy decisions, particularly in areas such as education, culture, heritage preservation, and diplomacy. Government agencies or think tanks may employ historians to provide context and perspective on contemporary issues.
  6. Journalist or Writer: Write articles, books, or documentaries that explore historical events, figures, or themes. Historians can bring their research skills to writing compelling narratives that educate and inform the public about the past.
  7. Editor or Publisher: Work in publishing houses, journals, or digital media outlets, editing and publishing works related to historical topics. Many PhD graduates in History find opportunities in academic publishing or general media, contributing their expertise to historical narratives.
  8. Cultural Resource Manager: Work in the preservation of historical landmarks, monuments, and cultural heritage sites. Cultural resource managers ensure that historical and cultural sites are protected and maintained.
  9. Genealogist: Use historical research techniques to trace family histories, providing services to individuals, corporations, or government agencies. Genealogy experts often work independently or with archival organizations.
  10. Consultant: Provide historical expertise to various organizations, including film and television production companies, political campaigns, or corporations. Consultants help ensure historical accuracy in media, projects, and business strategies.

Graduates of the PAIU Doctor of Business Administration program will be prepared to:

  • Evaluate business theory and practice from an international perspective.
  • Formulate effective solutions to complex, real-world business problems.
  • Apply current research literature to practical issues found within a business setting.
  • Evaluate scholarly research in business and management.
  • Design rigorous research in the English language that contributes to the professional body of
    business knowledge.
  • The ability to make effective decisions by integrating theories, insights, and practical
    knowledge.
  • Evaluate cultural, ethical, and global issues and their impact on the business environment.

By the end of the Master in Data Science program, students will be able to:

  • Demonstrate Proficiency in Data Analysis: Apply advanced statistical and analytical techniques to interpret and visualize data, deriving actionable insights for decision-making.
  • Utilize Machine Learning Algorithms: Leverage machine learning models and algorithms to develop predictive analytics and automate data processing tasks.
  • Conduct Data Mining: Execute data mining techniques to uncover patterns and trends within large datasets, contributing to strategic business initiatives.
  • Communicate Data Findings Effectively: Exhibit strong communication skills to convey complex data concepts and analytical results to both technical and non-technical audiences.
  • Implement Data Management Practices: Design and implement robust data management practices, ensuring data integrity, confidentiality, and accessibility across organizational systems.
  • Engage in Ethical Data Practices: Understand and apply ethical considerations surrounding data usage, compliance with regulations, and responsible data handling.
  • Foster Innovation through Data-Driven Solutions: Develop innovative data-driven strategies that support organizational goals and enhance operational efficiency.
  • Collaborate in Data-Driven Projects: Work effectively in interdisciplinary teams to analyze and solve complex problems, leveraging diverse skills and perspectives to achieve common objectives.

A PhD in Economics offers a wide array of career opportunities in various sectors, including academia, government, international organizations, consulting, finance, and research. Graduates typically pursue careers in the following areas:

  1. University Professor or Researcher: Teach and conduct research at academic institutions, contributing to the field through publications and conferences. Economics professors are at the forefront of advancing economic theory and providing expertise on economic issues.
  2. Economist in Government or Public Policy: Work for national or international government agencies, think tanks, or policy institutes, analyzing economic trends, evaluating government policies, and advising on economic issues such as taxation, trade, or development.
  3. Financial Analyst or Economist: Work in private financial institutions such as banks, investment firms, and insurance companies. These economists analyze market trends, make investment recommendations, and contribute to financial forecasting and risk management.
  4. International Economist: Work for international organizations like the World Bank, International Monetary Fund (IMF), or United Nations (UN) to analyze global economic conditions, provide economic advice, and develop strategies for economic development and international trade.
  5. Consultant: Provide expert economic analysis to private firms, government agencies, or NGOs. Economists in consulting firms help clients solve complex economic problems, such as pricing strategies, market entry, or economic forecasting.
  6. Data Scientist or Quantitative Analyst: Use econometric and statistical techniques to analyze large datasets and derive actionable insights. These professionals work in industries such as finance, healthcare, and technology, applying economic models to solve real-world problems.
  7. Economic Advisor: Serve as an expert to policymakers, corporations, or international organizations, advising on economic strategies, regulatory frameworks, and trade negotiations.
  8. Public Sector or Development Economist: Work for international development agencies, NGOs, or government agencies to promote economic development, reduce poverty, and design policies that foster economic growth and improve living standards in developing regions.
  9. Researcher in Private Sector: Conduct research for think tanks, private research firms, or corporations, analyzing market trends, consumer behavior, and economic conditions to inform business strategy or policy decisions.
  10. Corporate Strategist: Apply economic analysis to help businesses make strategic decisions, such as pricing, market expansion, and product development. Corporate strategists use economic models to predict market behavior and inform decision-making processes.

A PhD in International Relations opens doors to a wide range of career paths in academia, government, international organizations, think tanks, non-governmental organizations (NGOs), the private sector, and more. Graduates of this program typically pursue careers such as:

  1. University Professor: Teach courses in international relations, political science, and global studies, while conducting original research and publishing scholarly articles. Professors contribute to academic knowledge and engage in policy debates.
  2. Policy Analyst or Advisor: Work in government agencies, international organizations, or think tanks to provide expert analysis on foreign policy, international security, trade, or human rights. Policy advisors help shape national and international policy decisions.
  3. Diplomat or Foreign Service Officer: Represent a country’s interests abroad, negotiating with foreign governments, facilitating international cooperation, and promoting diplomatic relations. Diplomats are key players in conflict resolution, trade negotiations, and international agreements.
  4. International Development Specialist: Work with NGOs, international organizations, or governments to develop and implement programs aimed at promoting economic development, poverty reduction, and sustainable development in various regions.
  5. Human Rights Advocate: Work for organizations such as the United Nations, Amnesty International, or Human Rights Watch, advocating for the protection and promotion of human rights globally, particularly in conflict zones or developing countries.
  6. International Business Consultant: Advise multinational corporations on strategies for navigating the complexities of global trade, cross-border regulations, cultural differences, and international markets.
  7. Intelligence or Security Analyst: Provide analysis for government agencies, such as the CIA or MI6, focusing on international security issues, political instability, and threats to national interests. Analysts use their research skills to assess global trends and predict potential crises.
  8. International Law Expert: Specialize in the intersection of international relations and legal frameworks, working for governments, international courts, NGOs, or private law firms to advise on issues such as international treaties, human rights law, or conflict resolution.
  9. Political Risk Consultant: Analyze the political and economic risks that companies or investors face when entering new markets or regions, and provide advice on how to mitigate those risks. This role is often found in consulting firms or within financial institutions.
  10. Journalist or Foreign Correspondent: Report on international events, conflicts, and diplomatic relations for news organizations. Foreign correspondents provide first-hand accounts and in-depth analysis of global affairs.

A PhD in Law opens up numerous career pathways in various fields, from academia to policy-making, private practice, and international law. Graduates of the program often pursue careers in the following areas:

  1. University Professor: Teach law at the university level, mentor students, and engage in legal research and scholarship. Professors with a PhD in Law typically publish academic articles, contribute to legal theory, and influence legal education.
  2. Legal Researcher: Conduct research for universities, think tanks, policy institutes, or governmental bodies. Legal researchers analyze laws, assess policy implications, and contribute to shaping the future of legal practice.
  3. Judicial Roles: A PhD in Law can lead to career opportunities within the judiciary, such as a judge or law clerk, especially in high-level courts. Graduates may be involved in influencing legal precedents and judicial decisions.
  4. Corporate Counsel: Work in-house for large corporations or multinational companies, advising on legal matters related to business operations, contracts, mergers and acquisitions, and corporate governance.
  5. Public Policy Advisor: Influence legal reform and public policy as an advisor to government agencies, non-governmental organizations (NGOs), or international organizations. PhD graduates contribute their expertise in developing or reviewing laws and regulations.
  6. International Legal Consultant: Work with international organizations, governments, or non-profits to provide legal advice on global issues, such as human rights, environmental law, trade agreements, and international conflicts.
  7. Human Rights Advocate: Represent or advocate for human rights causes, working for international bodies like the United Nations or NGOs. PhD holders in Law often pursue careers in human rights law, focusing on global justice and equality.
  8. Criminal Defense or Prosecuting Attorney: While the PhD in Law is more research-oriented, many graduates combine their academic background with legal practice to work in the criminal justice system, either as defense attorneys or prosecutors.
  9. Legal Consultant or Expert: Serve as a consultant for law firms, governments, corporations, or international organizations. Legal consultants may provide expert opinions in complex legal cases or help organizations navigate regulatory frameworks.
  10. Policy Maker or Legislative Advisor: Work in government, contributing to the drafting, analysis, and revision of laws. This role requires in-depth legal knowledge and the ability to influence legislative processes and decisions.

A PhD in Psychology opens up numerous career opportunities in diverse fields, including academia, healthcare, business, government, and social services. Graduates of the program often pursue careers as:

  1. University Professor or Researcher: Teach at the college or university level while conducting original research. Psychology professors often publish in academic journals and contribute to the advancement of psychological science.
  2. Clinical Psychologist: Work in private practice, hospitals, or mental health clinics, diagnosing and treating a variety of psychological disorders. Clinical psychologists may specialize in areas such as child psychology, anxiety disorders, or family therapy.
  3. Counseling Psychologist: Provide therapy and counseling services to individuals, couples, or groups. Counseling psychologists often work in schools, mental health centers, or private practice, helping clients manage personal, social, and emotional challenges.
  4. Forensic Psychologist: Apply psychological principles in legal and criminal justice contexts. Forensic psychologists often work with law enforcement, lawyers, or courts to assess criminal behavior, witness credibility, or sentencing recommendations.
  5. Neuropsychologist: Specialize in understanding how brain injuries, neurological conditions, or cognitive disorders affect behavior and mental functioning. Neuropsychologists often work in medical settings or research institutions.
  6. Industrial-Organizational Psychologist: Work with organizations to improve employee performance, job satisfaction, and overall organizational effectiveness. I-O psychologists are involved in human resources, talent management, employee training, and organizational development.
  7. Health Psychologist: Focus on the relationship between mental and physical health, often working in medical settings to help individuals manage chronic illnesses, improve health behaviors, and address psychological aspects of physical health.
  8. Social Psychologist: Study how societal influences affect behavior, often working in research roles, policy development, or corporate settings to understand consumer behavior, group dynamics, and social perceptions.
  9. Educational Psychologist: Work in schools and educational institutions to help students with learning difficulties, emotional challenges, or behavioral issues, and provide guidance on best practices for teaching and learning.
  10. Research Scientist: Conduct research in academic, government, or private research labs, focusing on psychological phenomena, cognitive processes, or mental health interventions. Research psychologists often contribute to publishing new theories, therapies, or experimental findings.

Benefits of a PhD in Psychology

  • Expertise in Human Behavior: Gain an advanced understanding of psychological theories, human behavior, and mental health disorders, positioning you as an expert in the field.
  • Wide Range of Career Paths: A PhD in Psychology offers flexibility, with opportunities in clinical settings, academia, business, and research.
  • Impactful Work: Psychologists help improve the lives of individuals, organizations, and communities through therapy, research, and the development of effective interventions.
  • Job Security: The demand for trained psychologists, especially in clinical and counseling fields, remains strong, ensuring good career prospects.
  • High Earning Potential: Advanced degrees in psychology often lead to well-compensated positions, particularly in private practice, healthcare, and organizational consulting.

A PhD in Education provides graduates with opportunities for leadership roles in various sectors of education, including academia, policy-making, administration, and consulting. Graduates typically pursue careers in the following fields:

  1. University Professor or Researcher: Teach at the university level, conduct independent research, and contribute to the field through publications and academic conferences. Professors in education may specialize in areas such as curriculum development, educational leadership, or special education.
  2. Educational Administrator or Leader: Take on roles such as school superintendent, principal, or university administrator. PhD graduates in education provide leadership and oversight to educational institutions, shaping policy and managing day-to-day operations.
  3. Educational Consultant: Work with schools, districts, or educational organizations to provide expert advice on curriculum design, teacher training, school improvement strategies, or policy implementation. Consultants often work independently or as part of consulting firms.
  4. Policy Analyst or Advisor: Work for government agencies, think tanks, or non-governmental organizations (NGOs) to analyze and influence education policy. Policy advisors research educational trends, assess current policies, and provide recommendations for reform.
  5. Curriculum Developer: Design and evaluate educational programs and materials. Curriculum developers create resources that meet the needs of diverse learners and align with educational standards and goals.
  6. Special Education Director: Lead and manage special education programs, ensuring that students with disabilities receive the appropriate services and accommodations. This role involves overseeing individualized education plans (IEPs) and ensuring legal compliance.
  7. Higher Education Administrator: Manage operations within colleges or universities, including academic affairs, student services, admissions, or research administration. Higher education administrators ensure that institutions run efficiently and effectively.
  8. Educational Evaluator or Assessor: Conduct evaluations of educational programs, assessing their effectiveness and making recommendations for improvement. Evaluators work with schools, governments, or private organizations to measure the success of educational initiatives.
  9. Instructional Coordinator or Specialist: Focus on improving teaching methods and strategies within schools or districts. Instructional coordinators work to enhance teachers' skills, develop educational content, and ensure consistency across educational practices.
  10. Nonprofit or International Development Specialist: Work for nonprofit organizations or international development agencies that focus on improving education in underserved or developing regions. This role often involves designing and implementing educational programs, advocating for education policy changes, and assessing the effectiveness of education initiatives.

A PhD in Psychology opens up numerous career opportunities in diverse fields, including academia, healthcare, business, government, and social services. Graduates of the program often pursue careers as:

  1. University Professor or Researcher: Teach at the college or university level while conducting original research. Psychology professors often publish in academic journals and contribute to the advancement of psychological science.
  2. Clinical Psychologist: Work in private practice, hospitals, or mental health clinics, diagnosing and treating a variety of psychological disorders. Clinical psychologists may specialize in areas such as child psychology, anxiety disorders, or family therapy.
  3. Counseling Psychologist: Provide therapy and counseling services to individuals, couples, or groups. Counseling psychologists often work in schools, mental health centers, or private practice, helping clients manage personal, social, and emotional challenges.
  4. Forensic Psychologist: Apply psychological principles in legal and criminal justice contexts. Forensic psychologists often work with law enforcement, lawyers, or courts to assess criminal behavior, witness credibility, or sentencing recommendations.
  5. Neuropsychologist: Specialize in understanding how brain injuries, neurological conditions, or cognitive disorders affect behavior and mental functioning. Neuropsychologists often work in medical settings or research institutions.
  6. Industrial-Organizational Psychologist: Work with organizations to improve employee performance, job satisfaction, and overall organizational effectiveness. I-O psychologists are involved in human resources, talent management, employee training, and organizational development.
  7. Health Psychologist: Focus on the relationship between mental and physical health, often working in medical settings to help individuals manage chronic illnesses, improve health behaviors, and address psychological aspects of physical health.
  8. Social Psychologist: Study how societal influences affect behavior, often working in research roles, policy development, or corporate settings to understand consumer behavior, group dynamics, and social perceptions.
  9. Educational Psychologist: Work in schools and educational institutions to help students with learning difficulties, emotional challenges, or behavioral issues, and provide guidance on best practices for teaching and learning.
  10. Research Scientist: Conduct research in academic, government, or private research labs, focusing on psychological phenomena, cognitive processes, or mental health interventions. Research psychologists often contribute to publishing new theories, therapies, or experimental findings.

Benefits of a PhD in Psychology

  • Expertise in Human Behavior: Gain an advanced understanding of psychological theories, human behavior, and mental health disorders, positioning you as an expert in the field.
  • Wide Range of Career Paths: A PhD in Psychology offers flexibility, with opportunities in clinical settings, academia, business, and research.
  • Impactful Work: Psychologists help improve the lives of individuals, organizations, and communities through therapy, research, and the development of effective interventions.
  • Job Security: The demand for trained psychologists, especially in clinical and counseling fields, remains strong, ensuring good career prospects.
  • High Earning Potential: Advanced degrees in psychology often lead to well-compensated positions, particularly in private practice, healthcare, and organizational consulting.

A PhD in Education provides graduates with opportunities for leadership roles in various sectors of education, including academia, policy-making, administration, and consulting. Graduates typically pursue careers in the following fields:

  1. University Professor or Researcher: Teach at the university level, conduct independent research, and contribute to the field through publications and academic conferences. Professors in education may specialize in areas such as curriculum development, educational leadership, or special education.
  2. Educational Administrator or Leader: Take on roles such as school superintendent, principal, or university administrator. PhD graduates in education provide leadership and oversight to educational institutions, shaping policy and managing day-to-day operations.
  3. Educational Consultant: Work with schools, districts, or educational organizations to provide expert advice on curriculum design, teacher training, school improvement strategies, or policy implementation. Consultants often work independently or as part of consulting firms.
  4. Policy Analyst or Advisor: Work for government agencies, think tanks, or non-governmental organizations (NGOs) to analyze and influence education policy. Policy advisors research educational trends, assess current policies, and provide recommendations for reform.
  5. Curriculum Developer: Design and evaluate educational programs and materials. Curriculum developers create resources that meet the needs of diverse learners and align with educational standards and goals.
  6. Special Education Director: Lead and manage special education programs, ensuring that students with disabilities receive the appropriate services and accommodations. This role involves overseeing individualized education plans (IEPs) and ensuring legal compliance.
  7. Higher Education Administrator: Manage operations within colleges or universities, including academic affairs, student services, admissions, or research administration. Higher education administrators ensure that institutions run efficiently and effectively.
  8. Educational Evaluator or Assessor: Conduct evaluations of educational programs, assessing their effectiveness and making recommendations for improvement. Evaluators work with schools, governments, or private organizations to measure the success of educational initiatives.
  9. Instructional Coordinator or Specialist: Focus on improving teaching methods and strategies within schools or districts. Instructional coordinators work to enhance teachers' skills, develop educational content, and ensure consistency across educational practices.
  10. Nonprofit or International Development Specialist: Work for nonprofit organizations or international development agencies that focus on improving education in underserved or developing regions. This role often involves designing and implementing educational programs, advocating for education policy changes, and assessing the effectiveness of education initiatives.

A PhD in Law opens up numerous career pathways in various fields, from academia to policy-making, private practice, and international law. Graduates of the program often pursue careers in the following areas:

  1. University Professor: Teach law at the university level, mentor students, and engage in legal research and scholarship. Professors with a PhD in Law typically publish academic articles, contribute to legal theory, and influence legal education.
  2. Legal Researcher: Conduct research for universities, think tanks, policy institutes, or governmental bodies. Legal researchers analyze laws, assess policy implications, and contribute to shaping the future of legal practice.
  3. Judicial Roles: A PhD in Law can lead to career opportunities within the judiciary, such as a judge or law clerk, especially in high-level courts. Graduates may be involved in influencing legal precedents and judicial decisions.
  4. Corporate Counsel: Work in-house for large corporations or multinational companies, advising on legal matters related to business operations, contracts, mergers and acquisitions, and corporate governance.
  5. Public Policy Advisor: Influence legal reform and public policy as an advisor to government agencies, non-governmental organizations (NGOs), or international organizations. PhD graduates contribute their expertise in developing or reviewing laws and regulations.
  6. International Legal Consultant: Work with international organizations, governments, or non-profits to provide legal advice on global issues, such as human rights, environmental law, trade agreements, and international conflicts.
  7. Human Rights Advocate: Represent or advocate for human rights causes, working for international bodies like the United Nations or NGOs. PhD holders in Law often pursue careers in human rights law, focusing on global justice and equality.
  8. Criminal Defense or Prosecuting Attorney: While the PhD in Law is more research-oriented, many graduates combine their academic background with legal practice to work in the criminal justice system, either as defense attorneys or prosecutors.
  9. Legal Consultant or Expert: Serve as a consultant for law firms, governments, corporations, or international organizations. Legal consultants may provide expert opinions in complex legal cases or help organizations navigate regulatory frameworks.
  10. Policy Maker or Legislative Advisor: Work in government, contributing to the drafting, analysis, and revision of laws. This role requires in-depth legal knowledge and the ability to influence legislative processes and decisions.

Graduates of a PhD in Data and Cybersecurity can pursue advanced roles in both academia and industry. Career opportunities include:

  • Chief Information Security Officer (CISO)
  • Cybersecurity Research Scientist
  • Data Privacy Consultant
  • University Professor or Researcher
  • Lead Security Analyst

With the increasing demand for data protection and cybersecurity expertise, PhD graduates are essential for leading organizations in data security, developing cutting-edge solutions, and shaping policies for secure digital infrastructures.

A PhD in International Relations opens doors to a wide range of career paths in academia, government, international organizations, think tanks, non-governmental organizations (NGOs), the private sector, and more. Graduates of this program typically pursue careers such as:

  1. University Professor: Teach courses in international relations, political science, and global studies, while conducting original research and publishing scholarly articles. Professors contribute to academic knowledge and engage in policy debates.
  2. Policy Analyst or Advisor: Work in government agencies, international organizations, or think tanks to provide expert analysis on foreign policy, international security, trade, or human rights. Policy advisors help shape national and international policy decisions.
  3. Diplomat or Foreign Service Officer: Represent a country’s interests abroad, negotiating with foreign governments, facilitating international cooperation, and promoting diplomatic relations. Diplomats are key players in conflict resolution, trade negotiations, and international agreements.
  4. International Development Specialist: Work with NGOs, international organizations, or governments to develop and implement programs aimed at promoting economic development, poverty reduction, and sustainable development in various regions.
  5. Human Rights Advocate: Work for organizations such as the United Nations, Amnesty International, or Human Rights Watch, advocating for the protection and promotion of human rights globally, particularly in conflict zones or developing countries.
  6. International Business Consultant: Advise multinational corporations on strategies for navigating the complexities of global trade, cross-border regulations, cultural differences, and international markets.
  7. Intelligence or Security Analyst: Provide analysis for government agencies, such as the CIA or MI6, focusing on international security issues, political instability, and threats to national interests. Analysts use their research skills to assess global trends and predict potential crises.
  8. International Law Expert: Specialize in the intersection of international relations and legal frameworks, working for governments, international courts, NGOs, or private law firms to advise on issues such as international treaties, human rights law, or conflict resolution.
  9. Political Risk Consultant: Analyze the political and economic risks that companies or investors face when entering new markets or regions, and provide advice on how to mitigate those risks. This role is often found in consulting firms or within financial institutions.
  10. Journalist or Foreign Correspondent: Report on international events, conflicts, and diplomatic relations for news organizations. Foreign correspondents provide first-hand accounts and in-depth analysis of global affairs.

New Generation University. Bridging the skills gap in the tech field
through a unique educational model

Doğu Akdeniz Üniversitesi! On a beautiful island in Northern Cyprus lies a great academic  institute. By far the best in the region with many accreditation, serene environment including animals and accessibility friendly. Great place to learn, amazing places to visit, make new friends and beautiful memories. Some people are totally unfriendly and arrogrant but you have many amazing people around which is normal everywhere. I love my English professor Serife Sakalli Kurt she is just the best. There is free high-speed Wifi and bus transport throughout campus premises also endless places to hangout.

New & prospect students please read!

1, Booking your flight to EMU: It’s Northern Cyprus through Ercan International Airport and only Turkish Airlines fly here.

2, Don’t leave your admission and academics documents inside suitcase as you will be asked by the airport immigration/security.

3, For early arrival the university organizes airport pickups, temporal accommodation and orientation. Check out list of dormitories from my profile then click list.

4, You must read the student handbook & academic calendar! both available online from the university website if you don’t have a hard copy. Please Visit registrar’s office the moment you arrive to complete your registration then IT to get access to the school network and student portal. Getting Started EMU list is on my profile.

5, Check your student portal regularly as classes might change sometimes without any notification. Visit activity center for information about various clubs and their activities. Also follow the school social media accounts to stay informed.

Overall it’s a fantastic University apart from the language barrier sometimes

I will recommend Cyprus west university to everyone who wants to study abroad
The school is extremely doing good.

Amazing university, From the staff to the facilities everything is just remarkable. I completed my undergraduate here and it was an amazing learning experience academically as well as personal growth. Highly recommended to study here!!

I'm so grateful to God for giving me the opportunity to take my MBA course in Girne American University.
The university ties in America and Europe. At the same time, they are recognized globally.

They offer courses and programs leading to officially recognized higher education degrees such as pre-bachelor's degrees , bachelor's degrees, master's degrees and doctorate degrees in several areas of study.

Their facilities are good and they offer scholarships even in students abroad.
Thank you GIRNE AMERICAN UNIVERSITY 🥰🙏🥰

Well-Managed and Clean Campus!

I’ve been to MIT WPU Kothrud multiple times, and I must say it’s a great place! The campus is well-maintained and clean, providing a pleasant environment for both students and visitors. The facilities are well-managed, making it easy to navigate and find what you need. Whether you're attending an event or exploring the campus, you’ll appreciate the organized and welcoming atmosphere. Highly recommend visiting if you have the chance!

Review// EUL
Smooth admission process, diversity of international students, innovative and high quality education

One of the best universities of Northern Cyprus unlike many other universities, EUL gives you the access to your teachers.

The entire Facility is  large enough to move around smoothly from dormitories to all lecture rooms, library, admin offices.

Engineering and medical labs equipped with cutting edge tech.

Sports facilities constructed brilliantly to accommodate all kinds of sports and activities.

Have variety of affordable restaurants on campus.

All staff from international office, librarians, admin office, faculties, dormitories, management, facility care takers even the lawn mowers. all of them are highly supportive to every student regardless of their origin.

Spent 5 beautiful years of my life in this place. highly recommend this place for those looking for a peaceful pace and good quality time of university life

EUL facilitate its students with various restaurants, sports club, gym, dormitories and hospital. It has more than 10 thousand students from more than 80 countries. Means that it has a vast cultural environment. Having a pleasant and green environment for studies and social activities. Have a clean environment with lots of green grounds.
Simply, my experience here was excellent so far..

Vision of  AUC;
In the light of  science,

to provide high quality education and training,

to conduct research studies and publication activities,

to share the findings with the society at local and international level,

to contribute to the accumulation of global knowledge.

Mission of AUC;

• to preserve and protect cultural heritage of  Walled City of  Nicosia
• to contribute to the development of the region in the educational, cultural and socio-economic dimensions
• to educate students to have cultural values ​​at the national dimensions, to develop critical thinking skills, make analytical decisions and  generate solutions at global scale.

Language of Education

All education at AUC is carried out in English.

Academic Programs

In AUC there are currently three Faculties of education which include six undergraduate courses.

Academic Year

The AUC operates a two semester academic year, with the first semester commencing in September and concluding at the end of January and the second semester commencing in February and culminating in June.  There are also Summer School programs that will be available from the middle of June until end of August.

Campus

The campus of the American University of Cyprus is located within the ‘Walled City’ of Nicosia with a frequent bus service to surrounding areas.

AUC Life

The focus of AUC is to create a learning environment that encourages students to embrace the culture that surrounds us.  The university is an ever evolving institution that has grown at a rapid pace with the nucleus being centred round the qualified motivated lecturers, the friendly administrative team and ancillary staff.  The surrounding area is a mass of colour and charm enticing to the mind and challenging to the senses, with the university combining a modern and technical place of learning with the historic and cultural setting.

Urgent Message to New Students: Beware of Cyprus Health and Social Sciences University! 🚨

Attention to all new students considering Cyprus Health and Social Sciences University: Several Moroccan students, including myself and over 10 of my friends, have been victims of a disturbing scam perpetrated by this institution.

Here's what happened: Upon transferring to Cyprus Health and Social Sciences University, we were promised the opportunity to continue our studies and build a better future. However, after paying hefty fees and transferring our hard-earned credits, the university shockingly forced us to start from scratch, nullifying all our previous efforts. Despite our protests, requests for refunds were callously denied.

Now, faced with this betrayal, we are left with a difficult decision to make. We can either allow ourselves to be victims of this injustice or take action to hold the university accountable and prevent others from falling into the same trap.

As a community, we must stand together and demand justice. We have the power to raise awareness, report misconduct, and seek restitution for ourselves and future students who may be targeted by similar scams.

To all new students: Before enrolling in any institution, please heed this warning and thoroughly research its reputation and practices. Your education and future are too precious to be jeopardized by deceitful institutions.

Together, let's ensure that no student falls victim to exploitation and injustice

Ankara Sosyal Bilimler University (ASBU) is a public university located in Ankara, Turkey. It was established in 2013 and offers undergraduate and graduate programs in a variety of fields including social sciences, humanities, law, economics, and communication.

The university is known for its focus on social science research and its commitment to providing high-quality education. The faculty members at ASBU are experts in their fields and many are actively engaged in research projects both nationally and internationally.

ASBU offers a wide range of undergraduate programs including Business Administration, Economics, Political Science and International Relations, Sociology, Psychology, Law, and Communication. At the graduate level, the university offers programs in Business Administration, Economics, Political Science and International Relations, Law, and Communication.

In addition to its academic programs, ASBU is also known for its cultural and social activities. The university has a vibrant campus life with numerous student clubs and organizations. It also hosts a variety of events including seminars, conferences, and cultural activities throughout the year.

Overall, ASBU is a relatively new but rapidly growing university in Turkey that is dedicated to providing high-quality education and promoting social science research.

Orta Doğu Teknik Üniversitesi (ODTÜ) or Middle East Technical University (METU) is a public research university located in Ankara, the capital city of Turkey. It was established in 1956 with the aim of providing a high-quality education in engineering and natural sciences.

ODTÜ offers undergraduate and graduate programs in a wide range of fields, including engineering, natural sciences, social sciences, humanities, and art, design and architecture. The university is well-known for its strong programs in engineering and natural sciences, and it is regarded as one of the best universities in Turkey and the region.

The university has a beautiful and spacious campus that includes academic and administrative buildings, research centers, libraries, laboratories, sports facilities, dormitories, and social spaces. ODTÜ also has a strong research culture and has collaborations with national and international academic institutions and companies.

ODTÜ's mission is to provide a high-quality education that prepares students for their professional careers and contributes to the development of the country and the world. The university also aims to promote a culture of research and innovation and to serve as a hub for scientific and technological development.

GAU was founded in 1985 and has grown from its small beginnings with just seven students to being the 20,000 strong university that it is today 33 years later.  From its very inception, GAU has maintained close contractual ties with universities in North America and Europe.  GAU was one of the first university in Cyprus to receive recognition from YOK (Turkish Higher Education Council). This was followed by recognition from YODAK (Higher Education Council of Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus).  These required national accreditations were followed by a number of program accreditations and international recognitions.  This year is our 33th graduation ceremony that will occur in June of 2018 when more than 1500 graduates will earn their degrees and go on to advanced studies or to excellent jobs in Europe, the region and the World.

In 1995 GAU started its expansion into the international higher education sector.  Since then educational partnerships have been developed in India, Kazakhstan, Pakistan, Sri Lanka, Kyrgyzstan, Turkey, the USA, the UK, the Czech Republic, Hong Kong and Moldova.  These partnerships include student and faculty exchanges and the opportunity for students to experience different cultures and learning experiences.

The initial vision of the founders was to establish GAU as the pre-eminent institution of higher learning for the professions.  The university now includes degree offerings in Business and Economics, Politics, Health Sciences, Engineering, Communication, Humanities, Law, Pharmacy, Education, Architecture, Aviation, Marine, Nursing, Sports, Performing Arts and Tourism.

While heading towards the 50th year, GAU, throughout its 33 years of development the management, faculty and staff of the university have balanced the requirements for growth, with the need for high levels of quality, both in teaching and in the overall experience of each student.

Throughout its 33 year history, GAU has sought to optimize its use of the latest in technology and teaching methods.  While we have one of the highest Ph.D. to student ratios, we also have the highest computer to student ratio.  For the past five years the GAU library has been at the forefront of the revolution in library science; the implementation of digital library resources.  Many classes now include Power Point presentations and MP-4 download versions of the lectures.  The entire campus and all dormitories have Wi-Fi throughout.  GAU TV and Radio also broadcast selected lectures and seminars for student and faculty viewing.

GAU is continuing its global activities at an incredible pace today in light of its founding mission. As a member of the Universal Education Group and the American Education Consortium, GAU is moving firmly in achieving its targets while heading towards it’s 50th year in education.

The future is indeed bright.

New & prospect students please read!

1, Booking your flight to EMU: It’s Northern Cyprus through Ercan International Airport and only Turkish Airlines fly here.

2, Don’t leave your admission and academics documents inside suitcase as you will be asked by the airport immigration/security.

3, For early arrival the university organizes airport pickups, temporal accommodation and orientation. Check out list of dormitories from my profile then click list.

4, You must read the student handbook & academic calendar! both available online from the university website if you don’t have a hard copy. Please Visit registrar’s office the moment you arrive to complete your registration then IT to get access to the school network and student portal. Getting Started EMU list is on my profile.

5, Check your student portal regularly as classes might change sometimes without any notification. Visit activity center for information about various clubs and their activities. Also follow the school social media accounts to stay informed.

Overall it’s a fantastic University apart from the language barrier sometimes
